<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="52" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,653,1689]" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,905,930]" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">Comments:</emphasis>
The first mention of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Skalski" authorityYear="1992" box="[590,882,905,930]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spatalistiforma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="submerga">
<emphasis box="[590,882,905,930]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">Spatalistiforma submerga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Skalski, A. W." box="[929,1096,905,930]" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" pagination="195 - 208" refId="ref14182" refString="Skalski, A. W. (1976) Les lepidopteres fossiles de l'ambre, Etat actuel de nos connaissances (2 me partie). Linneana Belgica, 6 (8), 195 - 208." type="journal article" year="1976">Skalski (1976)</bibRefCitation>
must be considered a nomen nudum since it lacks a description. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Skalski, A. W." box="[693,862,941,966]" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" pagination="137 - 146" refId="ref14220" refString="Skalski, A. W. (1992) Studies on the Lepidoptera from fossil resins. Part III. Two new genera and species of Tortricidae from the Baltic amber. Annals of the Upper Silesian Museum in Bytom, Entomology, 3, 137 - 146." type="journal article" year="1992">Skalski (1992)</bibRefCitation>
subsequently validated the name by providing a description. 
<bibRefCitation author="Skalski, A. W." box="[290,455,977,1002]" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" pagination="137 - 146" refId="ref14220" refString="Skalski, A. W. (1992) Studies on the Lepidoptera from fossil resins. Part III. Two new genera and species of Tortricidae from the Baltic amber. Annals of the Upper Silesian Museum in Bytom, Entomology, 3, 137 - 146." type="journal article" year="1992">Skalski (1992)</bibRefCitation>
tentatively placed the fossil moth in the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[975,1080,977,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Tortricini">Tortricini</taxonomicName>
based on purported similarities in the wing venation with the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick, 1907" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1907" box="[575,872,1013,1038]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spatalistis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[575,691,1013,1038]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">Spatalistis</emphasis>
Meyrick, 1907
</taxonomicName>
. According to Skalski, among recent 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[1307,1432,1013,1038]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tortricidae</taxonomicName>
, only 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1907" box="[207,324,1049,1074]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spatalistis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[207,324,1049,1074]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">Spatalistis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[399,407,1064,1078]" fontSize="6" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">3</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[513,521,1064,1078]" fontSize="6" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">1</subScript>
veins stalked in both the fore and hindwing. However, Skalski acknowledged that the wing shape and at least two venational features of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Skalski" authorityYear="1992" box="[763,936,1088,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spatalistiforma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[763,936,1088,1113]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">Spatalistiforma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are different from those found in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1907" box="[1319,1436,1088,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spatalistis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1319,1436,1088,1113]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">Spatalistis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and allied genera.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,653,1689]" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">
There are no characters that convincingly assign the specimen to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[934,1060,1160,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tortricidae</taxonomicName>
, and there are subtle features that suggest it is not a tortricid. The overall shapes of both the forewing and hindwing are not particularly characteristic of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak" baseAuthorityYear="1998" box="[183,309,1232,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tortricidae</taxonomicName>
. In the forewing the termen is strongly angled inward, giving it an appearance that is more tineoid than tortricoid. In most tortricids, especially 
<taxonomicName box="[682,787,1268,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Tortricini">Tortricini</taxonomicName>
(and most other 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak &amp; Brown" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[998,1125,1268,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Tortricinae">Tortricinae</taxonomicName>
), the termen is oblique or slightly angled inward, giving the forewing a much more triangular appearance. Plus, the forewing pattern (which appears to be somewhat intact) is reminiscent of a tineid and not a tortricid. The unusual, long, slender scales from the costa of the forewing are present in no known tortricids, but we know of no other family with such forewing scales. The hindwing, likewise, has a shape that is more typical of Tineoidea and/or Yponomeutoidea (e.g. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Guenee" authorityYear="1845" box="[151,274,1448,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Plutellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Plutellidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stephens" authorityYear="1829" box="[284,465,1448,1473]" class="Insecta" family="Yponomeutidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Yponomeutidae</taxonomicName>
), somewhat broadly lanceolate-rounded. In 
<figureCitation box="[952,1031,1448,1473]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="12.[151,250,946,968]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,441,924]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1435,441,924]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 4. Spatalistiforma submerga Skalski, 1992. ZMCD (HT: 12-4/1957=LEP.SUCC.88 UZMC/AWS). Baltic amber. a. Dorsal view. Length of forewing 3 mm. b. Ventral view. For details of venation see Skalski (1992). Photos: Maria Heikkilä." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3094749/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">Fig. 4b</figureCitation>
the vague presence on the hindwing of a darker patch reminiscent of male secondary scales found in many tortricids is actually a detached leg with a tibial spur. Overall, the specimen bears little resemblance to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1907" box="[856,973,1520,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Spatalistis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[856,973,1520,1545]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">Spatalistis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has a strongly oblique forewing termen and raised scales on the forewing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,653,1689]" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">
This fossil was used as a calibration point in the divergence time study by 
<bibRefCitation author="Fagua, G. &amp; Condamine, F. L. &amp; Horak, M. &amp; Zwick, A. &amp; Sperling, F. A. H." box="[1093,1319,1592,1617]" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" pagination="449 - 466" refId="ref12375" refString="Fagua, G., Condamine, F. L., Horak, M., Zwick, A. &amp; Sperling, F. A. H. (2017) Diversification shifts in leafroller moths linked to continental colonization and the rise of angiosperms. Cladistics, 33 (5), 449 - 466. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / cla. 12185" type="journal article" year="2017">
Fagua 
<emphasis box="[1173,1234,1592,1617]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="52">et al.</emphasis>
(2017)
</bibRefCitation>
to give a minimum age to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Horak &amp; Brown" baseAuthorityYear="1991" box="[341,467,1628,1653]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Tortricinae">Tortricinae</taxonomicName>
. Based on the reasons given above, we find the original interpretation of the fossil as a tortricid unwarranted and its use as a calibration point for the purpose intended incorrect.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
